aa(lp261
VSo this was our approach,
p262
aVand it was simple materials,
p263
aVbut we thought about it carefully.
p264
aVAnd actually we know that those cells
p265
aVin the body, in the embryo, as they develop
p266
aVcan form a different kind of tissue, cartilage,
p267
aVand so we developed a gel that was slightly different
p268
aVin nature and slightly different chemistry,
p269
aVput it in there, and we were able to get
p270
aV100 percent cartilage instead.
p271
aa(lp272
VAnd this approach works really well, I think,
p273
aVfor pre-planned procedures,
p274
aVbut it's something you do have to pre-plan.
p275
aVSo for other kinds of operations,
p276
aVthere's definitely a need for other
p277
aVscaffold-based approaches.
p278
aVAnd when you think about designing
p279
aVthose other scaffolds, actually,
p280
aVyou need a really multi-disciplinary team.
p281
aVAnd so our team has chemists,
p282
aVit has cell biologists, surgeons, physicists even,
p283
aVand those people all come together
p284
aVand we think really hard about  designing the materials.
p285
aa(lp286
VBut we want to make them have enough information
p287
aVthat we can get the cells to do what we want,
p288
aVbut not be so complex as to make it difficult
p289
aVto get to clinic.
p290
aVAnd so one of the things we think about a lot
p291
aVis really trying to understand
p292
aVthe structure of the tissues in the body.
p293
aVAnd so if we think of bone,
p294
aVobviously my own favorite tissue,
p295
aVwe zoom in, we can see,
p296
aVeven if you don't know anything  about bone structure,
p297
aVit's beautifully organized,  really beautifully organized.
p298
aVWe've lots of blood vessels in there.
p299
aVAnd if we zoom in again, we see that the cells
p300
aVare actually surrounded by a 3D matrix
p301
aVof nano-scale fibers, and they give a lot
p302
aVof information to the cells.
p303
aVAnd if we zoom in again,
p304
aVactually in the case of bone, the matrix
p305
aVaround the cells is beautifully organized
p306
aVat the nano scale, and it's a hybrid material
p307
aVthat's part organic, part inorganic.
p308
aVAnd that's led to a whole field, really,
p309
aVthat has looked at developing materials
p310
aVthat have this hybrid kind of structure.
p311
aVAnd so I'm showing here just two examples
p312
aVwhere we've made some materials that have that sort of structure,
p313
aVand you can really tailor it.
p314
aVYou can see here a very squishy one
p315
aVand now a material that's also  this hybrid sort of material
p316
aVbut actually has remarkable toughness,
p317
aVand it's no longer brittle.
p318
aVAnd an inorganic material  would normally be really brittle,
p319
aVand you wouldn't be able to have
p320
aVthat sort of strength and toughness in it.
p321
aa(lp322
VOne other thing I want to quickly mention is that
p323
aVmany of the scaffolds we make  are porous, and they have to be,
p324
aVbecause you want blood vessels to grow in there.
p325
aVBut the pores are actually oftentimes
p326
aVmuch bigger than the cells,
p327
aVand so even though it's 3D,
p328
aVthe cell might see it more  as a slightly curved surface,
p329
aVand that's a little bit unnatural.
p330
aVAnd so one of the things you can think about doing
p331
aVis actually making scaffolds  with slightly different dimensions
p332
aVthat might be able to surround your cells in 3D
p333
aVand give them a little bit more information.
p334
aVAnd there's a lot of work going  on in both of these areas.
p335
aa(lp336
VNow finally, I just want to talk a little bit about
p337
aVapplying this sort of thing to cardiovascular disease,
p338
aVbecause this is a really big clinical problem.
p339
aVAnd one of the things that we know is that,
p340
aVunfortunately, if you have a heart attack,
p341
aVthen that tissue can start to die,
p342
aVand your outcome may not be very good over time.
p343
aVAnd it would be really great, actually,
p344
aVif we could stop that dead tissue
p345
aVeither from dying or help it to regenerate.
p346
aVAnd there's lots and lots of stem  cell trials going on worldwide,
p347
aVand they use many different types of cells,
p348
aVbut one common theme that seems to be coming out
p349
aVis that actually, very often, those cells will die
p350
aVonce you've implanted them.
p351
aVAnd you can either put them into the heart
p352
aVor into the blood system,
p353
aVbut either way, we don't seem to be able
p354
aVto get quite the right number of cells
p355
aVgetting to the location we want them to
p356
aVand being able to deliver the sort of beautiful
p357
aVcell regeneration that we would like to have
p358
aVto get good clinical outcomes.
p359
aa(lp360
VAnd so some of the things that we're thinking of,
p361
aVand many other people in the field are thinking of,
p362
aVare actually developing materials for that.
p363
aVBut there's a difference here.
p364
aVWe still need chemistry, we still need mechanics,
p365
aVwe still need really interesting topography,
p366
aVand we still need really interesting  ways to surround the cells.
p367
aVBut now, the cells also
p368
aVwould probably quite like a material
p369
aVthat's going to be able to be conductive,
p370
aVbecause the cells themselves will respond very well
p371
aVand will actually conduct signals  between themselves.
p372
aVYou can see them now
p373
aVbeating synchronously on these materials,
p374
aVand that's a very, very exciting development
p375
aVthat's going on.
